## Planning

When I see a task, make sure it has sensible timestamps and is properly scheduled. Every task must have a scheduled or due date so it can be reviewed or rescheduled — a vague wishlist item is better off deleted than left to be procrastinated indefinitely.

Whenever I identify a goal or task, I draft a plan of actionable subtasks in priority order so Henry is prepared. Example: for Henry's US internship [log/2026-05-07.md](../../log/2026-05-07.md), the top priority subtasks are:
1. Immigration — visa type and timing, supporting documents.
2. Relocation — flight and housing, with dates aligned (visa start → flight → housing → intern start).
3. Finances — US banking or transfer route for payroll, currency conversion ahead of expenses, emergency cash.
4. Communications — US SIM live before landing.

This also applies to long-term goals, so I open a task for Henry to discuss his research plan during internship.

## Task DSL

Open tasks live in Henry's notes as Obsidian-style checkboxes:

- `[ ]` todo, `[/]` in progress, `[x]` done with `✅ YYYY-MM-DD`
- ⏳ scheduled — when to prepare/act
- 🛫 start, 📅 due — the range a task can be scheduled
- 🔁 recurring
    - relative, e.g. `🔁 every 3 days`, used together with scheduled
    - absolute, e.g. `🔁 every weekday`, `🔁 every week on Monday`, used without scheduled date

When a task status changes during a session:
- Tick `[ ]` → `[/]` while in progress, `[x]` + completion date `✅ YYYY-MM-DD` when finished.
- Update the source file directly.
